# Python Module Design

- Keep an explicit public API for each module or subpackage (clear exported functions/classes and stable names).
- Keep each module focused on one responsibility area and extract helpers when scope expands.
- Prefer descriptive module names that communicate ownership and intent; avoid catch-all growth in `utils.py`.
- Keep `__init__.py` light: exports, constants, and package metadata only; no runtime side effects.
- Co-locate helpers near the domain that uses them unless they are genuinely cross-domain.
- Keep function signatures focused and pass typed data objects instead of long unstructured argument lists.
- Use dependency injection boundaries for external services, file I/O, and API clients so core logic remains testable.
- Prefer composition of small builder/helper functions over single large multi-purpose functions.
- Exception: temporary adapter modules are acceptable during refactors when they are marked for removal and remain thin.
